# data-visualization / gnuplot

gnuplot renders 2D/3D plots from plain-text `.gp` scripts, fully headless in batch
mode. The deliverable is a deterministic, version-controllable script plus its data;
the same script + data + gnuplot version produces byte-stable vector SVG/PDF output.

controls do
  data-visualization.title: { label: "Title", type: "text" }
end

## Required reading

- Official gnuplot docs (gnuplot project, gnuplot license): https://gnuplot.readthedocs.io/en/latest/
- gnuplotting.org output-terminal recipes (community): http://gnuplotting.org/output-terminals/index.html
- gnuplot source repo (gnuplot dev team, gnuplot license): https://github.com/gnuplot/gnuplot
- No official Anthropic/Claude skill exists — community resources only: https://github.com/anthropics/skills

## Render

```bash
brew install gnuplot && gnuplot --version
# author plot.gp beginning with `set terminal svg size W,H` + `set output 'out.svg'`
gnuplot plot.gp
# PDF: use pdfcairo terminal; PNG: use pngcairo terminal
```

## Failure modes

- Using an interactive terminal (`qt`/`x11`/`wxt`) in a headless pipeline — requires a
  DISPLAY and pops/blocks. Always `set terminal svg`/`pdfcairo`/`pngcairo` to a file.
- Forgetting `set output 'file'` — output goes to stdout / never written.
- Time/date auto-stamps or unpinned fonts break byte-stable reproducibility.
- Terminal defaults shift across gnuplot majors — pin 6.0.x in the toolchain manifest.
- pdfcairo/svg embed font names, not glyphs — non-portable if the font is missing on
  the reader's machine; stick to common fonts or use cairolatex/epslatex + a LaTeX step.
